The Importance Of This Question: Determining this NFL teams can focus more on the significant variables and tailor their team to give them a higher chance at winning. IN return, winning cause more people to come to games and higher attendance could turn into higer profit.

The Data: The comes from NFL website and is data contains 29 variables and 67,661 observations. It is a mixture of numeric and character fields.

For my last model I will create a new data frame and check the error rate of the model by creating a dummy variable to predict wins.

mainNFL2 <- select(mainNFL, score_margin, position, year, season, home_or_away, games_started, rushing_yards, rushing_tds, receptions, longest_reception, receiving_tds, fumbles_lost)

mainNFL2$win = as.factor(ifelse(mainNFL2$score_margin > 0,1,0))

I am creating a new training and testing data set.

set.seed(1)
train = sample(1:nrow(mainNFL2), 0.75*nrow(mainNFL2))
mainNFL2.train = mainNFL2[train, ]
mainNFL2.test = mainNFL2[-train, ]

Going to start with a classification tree and then create a train and test data for probability and predcitons. Setting both thresholds to 50 percent.

my.class.tree = tree(win ~ . -score_margin, data = mainNFL2.train)
plot(my.reg.tree)
text(my.reg.tree, pretty =0)

prob.train = predict(my.class.tree, newdata=mainNFL2.train)[,2]
prob.test = predict(my.class.tree, newdata=mainNFL2.test)[,2]

pred.train = ifelse(prob.train >= 0.5, 1, 0)
pred.test = ifelse(prob.test >= 0.5, 1, 0)

The train model has a 38.7 percent error rate and the test model as a 40% error rate. Both models performed well.

conf.train = table(pred.train, mainNFL2.train$win)
conf.test = table(pred.test, mainNFL2.test$win)
error.train = 1 - sum(diag(conf.train)) / sum(conf.train)
error.train
## [1] 0.387234
error.test = 1 - sum(diag(conf.test)) / sum(conf.test)
error.test
## [1] 0.4042553

In conclusion in order to predict scrore margin the best predictor is rushing yards. If we were to go accroding to the regression tree the next best predictor would be rushing touchdowns. However, the random foresst model says longest reception is the next best variable. I believe that rushing yards and rushing touch downs are the two best. Those variables are highly significant.
